Lab Goals:¶

  1. Get overview about Hive.
  2. Learn how to use Hive to create tables and perform queries against them.

Lab Tasks:¶

  1. Task 1: Create and populate Table (o.5 points)
  2. Task 2: Perform queries against the created table (0.5 points)
  3. Task 3: Data partitioning (1 point)

Introduction:¶

In this session we are going to work with Apache Hive. Apache Hive is an open source software which facilitates reading, writing, and managing large datasets in distributed storage (HDFS/Hbase) using SQL-like queries.

  • Hive uses HiveQL.

  • it generates MapReduce jobs that run on Hadoop cluster. ### Hive Basic operations: Here are some operations that Hive can performs:

  • Create databaseCREATE DATABASE d.

    • CREATE DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS d

  • Drop databaseCREATE DATABASE d.

    • DROP DATABASE IF NOT EXISTS d

  • Create table

    CREATE TABLE tablename (colname DATATYPE, ...)
ROW FORMAT DELIMITED
FIELDS TERMINATED BY char
LOCATION 'user/cloudera/a';

  • Querying table

    • sql queries e.g. SELECT a FROM B

  • Loading data

    • hdfs dfs -mv /a/b.txt /user/hive/warehouse/b/
    • INSERT INTO TABLE a SELECT * FROM b;

  • Create partitioned table accounts_by_State 
    CREATE Table accounts_by_State(
cust_id INT,
fname STRING,
lname STRING,
address STRING,
city STRING,
zipcode STRING
)
PARTITIONED BY (state STRING);

  • From Hive Shell or from Hue Query Editor run the following commands that will enable dynamic partitioning:

    SET  hive.exec.dynamic.partition = true;
SET  hive.exec.dynamic.partition.mode = nonstrict;
SET hive.exec.max.dynamic.partitions.pernode=400;

  • Load data into accounts_by_State and dynamically create partitions by state

    INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE accounts_by_State
PARTITION(state)
SELECT cust_id, fname, lname,address, city, zipcode, state 
FROM accounts;
  • Now the get the first name and the last name of all customers from "NV" state.

It might be tricky in this small dataset but in a real life scenario while dealing with big data, in case of accounts_by_state it will only access the files which is partitioned by state = 'NV' and won't need to iterate over the whole dataset to find the required query same case in accounts_by_state_city it will deal only with the files in the query written, so it should be even faster¶

  • Create partitioned table accounts_by_State_city

CREATE Table accounts_by_State_City( cust_id INT, fname STRING, lname STRING, address STRING, zipcode STRING ) PARTITIONED BY (state STRING, city STRING)

  • insert

INSERT OVERWRITE TABLE accounts_by_State_City PARTITION(state,city) SELECT cust_id, fname, lname,address, zipcode, state, city FROM accounts;

Task 5: Change Storage Formats¶

We will use Hive to transform data formats from textual into other binary formats. We can transform the original accounts table into AVRO once and into Parquet another time.

  • create table accounts_avro and instruct Hive to store it as AVRO
  • Similarly, create table accounts_parquet
  • Load the data from the original table accounts into the target tables via insert from select statements
  • Finally, run the same queries from Task 3 to make sure that everything works fine.

Using the following schema¶

('avro.schema.literal'='{
  "type" : "record",
  "name" : "Accounts",
  "doc" : "Schema for the accounts_avro table",
  "fields" : [ {
    "name" : "cust_id",
    "type" : [ "int", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "fname",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "lname",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "address",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "city",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "zipcode",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
  }, {
    "name" : "state",
    "type" : [ "string", "null" ]
